cussions, as many researchers chose to speak when communicating their findings with other speaking peers, even though the conference was about SLs [4]. Another user, an associate professor at the University of Bergen [5], posted a large thread on the topic of #NoTalkTISLR, arguing that future iterations of the conference should “leave talking at the door” [6]. While some might argue that it’s excluding those that cannot use or understand signed languages, he argues that it’s “encouraging everyone to negotiate an inclusive communication. It's sign language research, we *need* to sign. No exceptions” [6]. Additionally, he raises another point regarding the usage of IS vs ASL, relating it to how English, as the default language of academia, already serves as a large barrier to entry. Finally, a Linguist at the University of the West Indies [7] further supports this point, stating that “English is currently a barrier to many” and “it would shift things in interesting and productive ways” [8].%0a%3c 	I was unable to provide any information on TISLR 15 and if it will implement any sort of no-talking policies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [1] - www.tislr2022.jp/abouttislr/%0a%3c [2] - www.tislr2022.jp/%0a%3c [3] - https://twitter.com/marta_morgado%0a%3c [4] - https://twitter.com/marta_morgado/status/1575413327051759616%0a%3c [5] -https://twitter.com/c_borstell%0a%3c [6] - https://twitter.com/c_borstell/status/1178221219696517125%0a%3c [7] - https://twitter.com/benbraithwaite%0a%3c [8] - https://twitter.com/benbraithwaite/status/1575870296820748288%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must